# Project Identity: abuse-detection-ml

Production-grade ML system for detecting malicious prompts and jailbreak attempts in user interactions with AI assistants.

## Technology Stack

Backend Language: Python 3.10+

ML Framework: scikit-learn, joblib, imbalanced-learn

Data Processing: pandas, numpy, Hugging Face Datasets

Experiment Tracking: MLflow (local file backend)

Model Registry: Local filesystem (models/) versioned with Git‑LFS (optional)

API Layer: FastAPI (served via uvicorn inside container)

Frontend: React 18+ with TypeScript, Vite, Material-UI (MUI)

Containerization: Docker, Docker Compose (all services defined in docker-compose.yml)

Development Environment: Jupyter notebooks (notebooks/) for exploration; refactored code in src/; frontend in frontend/

Secrets: .env file mounted into containers (never committed)

Data Storage: Local volumes (./data, ./models, ./frontend/node_modules) persisted outside containers

## Development Workflow

Data Acquisition:

Use public datasets (e.g., guychuk/benign-malicious-prompt-classification) via Hugging Face datasets.

Data is downloaded once and cached in a local volume (./data/cache).

Model Development:

Iterate in Jupyter notebooks (notebooks/).

Once stable, refactor into Python modules (src/).

All experiments are tracked via MLflow (local directory mlruns/).

Frontend Development:

Located in frontend/ with Vite dev server.

Hot-reload enabled when running in Docker Compose (via volume mount).

Material-UI (MUI) components for consistent, accessible design.

Version Control:

Commit code and configuration: git commit -m "Description".

Push to GitHub: git push origin main.

CI: GitHub Actions run linting and unit tests; model artifacts are not committed (ignored via .gitignore).

Local Container Deployment:

Build images: docker-compose build

Run full stack: docker-compose up

Services:

api: FastAPI app (served via uvicorn inside container)

frontend: React + Vite dev server  – or production build served by nginx (port 80)

mlflow: tracking server (port 5000) – optional for advanced experiment management

We also must have a run.sh script that starts everything for me and tells me what port for each (frontend and backend) service.

# ARCHITECTURE & SCALABILITY

Modular design:

src/data/: Data loading, preprocessing, splitting, and dataset versioning.

src/models/: Model definition, training, calibration, evaluation, and registry.

src/api/: FastAPI endpoints for predictions.

src/utils/: Shared utilities (logging, config, metrics).

notebooks/: Exploratory analysis and experiment notebooks.

frontend/: React application with Vite, organised by features (e.g., components/, pages/, services/).

Configuration‑driven:

All paths, model hyperparameters, thresholds, and dataset names are controlled via environment variables (defined in .env).

Example variables:

MODEL_PATH=/app/models/model.pkl

THRESHOLD=0.54

DATASET_NAME=guychuk/benign-malicious-prompt-classification

ENVIRONMENT=development

VITE_API_BASE_URL=http://api:8000 (or whatever empty port is assigned to api service)

Experiment tracking (optional): MLflow logs parameters, metrics, and artifacts for each training run. The local mlruns directory is mounted as a volume to persist across container restarts.

Model versioning:

Each trained model is saved with a version tag (e.g., v1.0.0) and accompanied by a config.json containing the threshold, feature names, and calibration method.

The API can load a specific version via the MODEL_VERSION environment variable.

Service discovery:

Containers communicate via Docker Compose service names (e.g., frontend → api:8000(or whatever port is assigned to api service)).

No external service dependencies.

# INTERNATIONALIZATION & ACCESSIBILITY

Plain English first: All UI text must be clear to non‑technical moderators. Avoid jargon like “TF‑IDF”, “logistic regression”. Use “harmful content”, “blocked”, “confidence score”.

Right‑to‑left support: MUI provides built‑in RTL support; structure layouts to accommodate future Arabic/other RTL languages.

Keyboard navigation: All interactive elements must be focusable and operable via keyboard (Tab, Enter, Space) – MUI components generally handle this, but verify.

Screen reader compatibility: Use proper ARIA labels, semantic HTML (MUI components support this). Test with screen readers.

# UI/UX FOR NON‑TECHNICAL USERS

Clarity over cleverness: Use plain language for labels and instructions. Every input, toggle, and configuration option must have a MUI Tooltip that explains its purpose in simple terms.

Confidence indicators: Show visual indicators (e.g., stars, colored badges) for prediction confidence (High/Medium/Low) based on calibrated probability.

Error messages: Never show raw Python tracebacks. Display friendly messages with suggested actions (e.g., “The model is temporarily unavailable. Please try again later.”).

Empty states: If no results, show helpful guidance (e.g., “Enter a prompt to analyze”).

Progress indicators: For long‑running operations (e.g., training), show spinners or step indicators.

Consistent layout: Use MUI’s theming system to maintain a consistent look across all pages.

Confirm destructive actions: If an action clears data or runs a long operation, show a confirmation dialog.

# DATA & SOURCE HANDLING

Dataset versioning: Record the exact dataset version (commit hash or HF dataset version) used for training.

Data splits: Always separate train/validation/test sets; never use test data for model selection.

Source separation: For production, distinguish between internal user queries (to be logged) and public test examples.

Metadata preservation: When saving datasets, keep all original fields for traceability.

Local caching: Datasets are cached in a Docker volume (data_cache) to avoid repeated downloads.

# CODING STANDARDS

Backend:

Type hints for all Python functions.

Google‑style docstrings.

PEP8; use black, isort, and flake8 in CI.

Structured logging with levels; never log PII.

Frontend:

TypeScript strict mode; explicit interfaces for props and state.

Functional components with hooks.

Absolute imports using @ alias configured in Vite.

Prettier and ESLint for consistent formatting.

Error boundaries to isolate component crashes.

# FUTURE PROOFING

Add new datasets without friction:

Place dataset loading script in src/data/loaders/.
Register the dataset in src/data/registry.py.
Update configuration to point to the new dataset.
Add new model architectures:

Create a new class in src/models/ (e.g., TransformerModel).
Implement the required interface (.fit(), .predict_proba(), .save(), .load()).
Register in src/models/registry.py.
Environment‑aware defaults: Use environment variables to switch between different local paths or dataset versions.

Backward compatibility: When updating the model’s prediction format, version the API endpoint (/v1/predict, /v2/predict).

Feature flags: Use environment variables to enable/disable experimental features (e.g., a new calibration method).

Configuration‑driven UI: Generate input fields from a schema (e.g., JSON) so new features can be added without rewriting JSX.

# PERFORMANCE & SECURITY

Caching: Cache prediction results for identical prompts (with TTL) to reduce compute load; implemented via functools.lru_cache or a simple in‑memory dict.

Rate limiting: Not required for local single‑user deployment, but code should be structured to allow easy addition of slowapi or similar later.

Input sanitization: Before passing prompts to the model, strip control characters and truncate to max length (configurable).

No sensitive data in logs: Ensure prompts are not logged in plain text; use hashing for debugging if needed.

Model integrity: Model files are stored locally and can be checksum‑verified on load.

Prompt injection protection: Although the model is the detector, still sanitize inputs to the API layer.

# TESTING

Unit tests: Test data loading, preprocessing, and metric calculations (using pytest for backend, Jest for frontend).

Integration tests: Test the full prediction pipeline (model loading + inference) on a small sample.

Smoke tests: Verify the API endpoint and frontend build.

Test isolation: Tests run inside a dedicated Docker container (or using local tooling with mocked dependencies).

# DOCUMENTATION

README.md: Overview, setup instructions (including Docker Compose), quick start, and how to add a new dataset/model.

docs/development.md: Detailed guide for contributors (including how to run containers, add dependencies, frontend development).

docs/deployment.md: Local container deployment steps (already covered by README).

API documentation: Auto‑generated via FastAPI’s OpenAPI (accessible at /docs when container is running).

# GLOBAL AUDIT PROTOCOLS & ENFORCEMENT

## ✅ Enforcement

### 🎯 Automatic Inference

Even without a keyword, analyze the nature of the task and automatically run the most appropriate sweep(s) (non exhaustive):

Examples of implicit triggers:

Changing dataset loading code? → Implicitly triggers a Data Integrity Sweep (checking splits, leakage)

Modifying model architecture? → Implicitly triggers an AI Sweep (checking hyperparameters, overfitting)

Touching API endpoints? → Implicitly triggers a Security Sweep (checking input validation, rate limiting)

Refactoring evaluation metrics? → Implicitly triggers a Logic Sweep (checking correctness, edge cases)

Updating threshold selection logic? → Implicitly triggers a Performance Sweep (checking trade-offs)

Changing Dockerfiles or compose files? → Implicitly triggers a DevOps Sweep (checking environment variables, health checks)

Modifying frontend components? → Implicitly triggers a UX Sweep (checking clarity, accessibility, empty states)

### 📋 Core Audit Protocols

> **Note:** Note: The Core Audit Protocols (`(audit:logic)`, `(audit:ux)`, `(audit:sec)`, `(audit:arch)`, `(audit:perf)`, `(audit:test)`, `(audit:docs)`, `(audit:compliance)`, `(audit:devops)`, `(audit:ai)`, `(audit:env)`, `(audit:maintain)`) are defined in the Global User Rules. Refer to them for specific persona definitions and actions.

### 🔧 Ad-Hoc Sweeps

If a task falls outside these core categories (e.g., Performance, Accessibility, Database Integrity), invent and apply an appropriate "Ad-Hoc Sweep" with the same rigor:

1. Define a clear persona
2. Define specific action items to check
3. Provide structured output

### ⚡ Priority Rules

- **Explicit keyword** → If provided, prioritize that specific audit
- **Automatic inference** → If no keyword, infer the most relevant sweep(s)
- **Multiple sweeps** → Complex changes may trigger multiple audits (e.g., UI + Security)

### 📝 Documentation

- **Silent by default**: Perform audits in the background. Only report findings if **critical issues** or **high-value improvements** are discovered.
- **Concise**: Keep responses focused on the requested task. Do not explain "why" no audit was needed.

# DATA PROVENANCE & AUDIT

Dataset lineage: Record the source, version, and preprocessing steps for every dataset used (store in data/README.md or MLflow).

Model card: Maintain a model card (in docs/) that describes:

Intended use

Training data

Performance metrics (by subgroup if possible)

Known limitations (e.g., misses sophisticated jailbreaks)

Ethical considerations

Prediction logging: In the local API, log anonymized queries, predicted labels, confidence scores, and timestamps to a file (rotated) for monitoring and retraining decisions. Ensure no PII is logged.

Confidence scoring: For each prediction, output a calibrated probability along with the binary label.

# ERROR HANDLING & RECOVERY

Model loading failure: If the model cannot be loaded from the specified path, fall back to a simple rule‑based classifier (if implemented) and log an alert. Otherwise, return a 500 with a clear message.

Prediction timeout: Set a timeout for inference (via asyncio or thread); if exceeded, return a 503 with a retry‑after hint.

Input validation: Reject inputs that are too long or contain invalid characters with a clear error message (400).

Graceful degradation: If the calibrated probabilities are unavailable (e.g., calibration step failed), fall back to raw model probabilities.

# DEPLOYMENT & DEVOPS

Container health checks: The API container must expose a /health endpoint that returns 200 when ready. Docker Compose will use this for dependency ordering.

Configuration validation: On startup, check that all required environment variables are set; exit with a clear error if missing.

Model artifact loading: The model is loaded from a local path (mounted volume). The container expects the model to be present; if not, it can be trained on first run via an entrypoint script.

Logging: Use JSON structured logging; logs are written to stdout and collected by Docker.

Metrics: Expose Prometheus metrics (optional) at /metrics for local monitoring.

Data persistence: Use Docker volumes for models/, data/, mlruns/, and frontend/node_modules to preserve state across container restarts.

No cloud dependencies: All services run locally; internet may be used only for downloading datasets or base images.
